// TEST: exec_ts_lambda_untyped_param
// EXPECT: output "12"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python
//
// A lambda whose parameter carries no type annotation, stored in a binding with
// no contextual type and then invoked (the type-zoo / task-api / inventory /
// todo-list cluster). Bock lambdas usually omit param types; the AIR carries no
// inferred type, so emitting `(x) => …` is an *implicit any* that `tsc --strict`
// (`noImplicitAny`) rejects (TS7006). The fix annotates an un-typed lambda param
// as `any` (always type-checks; a contextual call site would have inferred it
// anyway), validated here against the (untyped) js/python emits.
//
// Restricted to js/ts/python: rust and go reject an un-annotated, un-contextual
// closure param (`x * 3` with `x: interface{}` / untyped) — a separate backend
// inference gap reported as an OPEN. Widen once those infer the param type.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn main() -> Void {
  let triple = (x) => x * 3
  println("${triple(4)}")
}
